<text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
  <body>
    <div rend="parallel">
      <lg xml:id="TolE093">
<l>aṇṇa naṇṇiya paṉmutaṉ maruṅki</l>
<l>ṉānuṉi parantu meyyuṟa voṟṟat</l>
<l>tāmiṉitu piṟakkun takāra nakāram</l>
      </lg>
      <lg xml:lang="en">
<l><foreign xml:lang="ta">t</foreign> [and] <foreign xml:lang="ta">ṇ</foreign>, they are easily produced by the tip of the tongue</l>
<l>spread out, [its] body touching [and] striking the place adjacent</l>
<l>to the teeth [where they] join the palate.<note
              place="foot"><foreign xml:lang="ta">t</foreign> and <foreign xml:lang="ta">n</foreign>
          are described early as post-dental consonaants which are articulated by the blade of the
          tongue in proper contact with the junction of the root of the upper teeth with the palate.</note></l>
      </lg>
    </div>
  </body>
